{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1607"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1607"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.17,0.56,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1607"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44926"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1607"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1607"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29827"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1207"},{"type":"tags","id":"2177"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2517"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44926"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department immediately following a blow to the right eye during a game of competitive baseball. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally, the intraocular pressures are normal and blood can be seen in the anterior chamber (hyphaema) of the right eye (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is this patient most at risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Optic atrophy","Impaired accomodation","Corneal blood staining","Raised intraocular pressures","Peripheral anterior synechiae"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a pool of blood in the inferior aspect of the anterior chamber of the eye, consistent with hyphaema. Approximately one-third of patients with hyphaema will have subsequent \u003Cstrong\u003Eraised intraocular pressures\u003C/strong\u003E secondary to trabecular meshwork obstruction. Management of uncomplicated hyphaema is conservative with use of an eye shield, limited activity and head elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther potential complications including \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic atrophy\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorneal blood staining\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eperipheral anterior synechiae\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eimpaired accomodation\u003C/strong\u003E are less common. Optic atrophy can result from persistent raised intraocular pressures. A long-standing hyphaema can result in corneal blood staining and peripheral anterior synechiae. Peripheral anterior synechiae refers to the peripheral iris attaching to the anterior chamber angle. Accomodation impairment is uncommon and seen in less than 10% of patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A raised intraocular pressure is an important potential complication to look for after eye injury."],"references":["Walton W, Von Hagen S, Grigorian R, Zarbin M. Management of traumatic hyphema. Survey of Ophthalmology. 2002;47(4):297-334. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12161209/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29827"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1607"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15969"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media